ce:section.ce:para:
The DFT method was used to investigate the unique sensing of ammonia. A graphitic fragment with nitrogen doping and edge functional groups was used as the carbon dot model. An ammonia molecule was placed at the top of carbon dot, and the dimers were optimized. The optimized structure was then computed using single point calculation with counterpoise correction (Table 1
                        ). The distances between these small molecules and the carbon dot were approximately 2.81–3.73 Å, indicating favorable interactions between them. Fig. 10
                        a and b show the optimized conformations of the dimers. It was found that the nitrogen atom of the ammonia pointed toward the surface of the graphitic sheet, whereas the hydrogen atoms pointed away (Fig. 10a). This was consistent with previous computational studies of the interaction between ammonia and graphene sheet [55,56]. The interaction energy (I.E.) between the carbon dot and ammonia was then calculated. In addition, the I.E. values of the complexes with and formaldehyde, methanol, and water were also computed (Fig. S3, Supplementary Information). As can be seen from Table 1, the IEs of the complexes ranked as follows: ammonia > methanol > formaldehyde > water, showing a good agreement with the electronic nose results in which the strongest signal was obtained from ammonia vapor followed by methanol, formaldehyde, and water. The carbon dot-ammonia complex exhibited the most negative IE value, reflecting the strongest interaction. For all optimized structures, the sensing mechanism was found to be physisorption, as no chemical bonding took place between the solvent molecules and carbon dot. This suggested that carbon dot-integrated sensing is reproducible and reusable, consistent with the results of the electronic nose experiments.
